Next, you need to connect the LCD screen to the Arduino board. The LCD screen can be controlled using the LiquidCrystal_I2C library, which can be installed via the Arduino IDE [[2](https://arduinogetstarted.com/tutorials/arduino-display-temperature-from-lm35-sensor-on-lcd)]. To control the brightness of the LCD screen, a potentiometer can be used. The potentiometer is connected to the Arduino board, and the value read from the potentiometer is used to set the brightness of the LCD screen [[3](https://www.hackatronic.com/arduino-with-temperature-sensor-interfacing-lcd-and-lm35/)].

To support Azure Active Directory (AAD) SSO tokens in Apache Airflow, you'll need to configure the `auth_backend` and `auth_type` settings in your `airflow.cfg` file. Here's an example configuration:
```yaml
[core]
auth_backend = airflow.contrib.auth.backends.azure_active_directory

[azure_active_directory]
client_id = <your_client_id>
client_secret = <your_client_secret>
tenant_id = <your_tenant_id>
auth_endpoint = https://login.microsoftonline.com/<your_tenant_id>/oauth2/v2.0/token
token_endpoint = https://login.microsoftonline.com/<your_tenant_id>/oauth2/v2.0/token
```
Replace `<your_client_id>`, `<your_client_secret>`, and `<your_tenant_id>` with the values from your Azure AD application.

Additionally, you'll need to configure the `auth_type` setting to use the `azure_active_directory` backend:
```yaml
[api]
auth_type = azure_active_directory
```
This will enable AAD SSO token authentication for the Airflow API.

To use the `azure_active_directory` backend, you'll also need to install the `azure-identity` and `azure-common` libraries. You can do this by running the following command:
```
pip install azure-identity azure-common
```
Once you've updated your `airflow.cfg` file and installed the required libraries, restart your Airflow webserver and scheduler to apply the changes.
